{"chunk_id": "4726be23-55d5-483d-a8a2-f60d3c750ba5", "source_database": "ICMR", "document_title": "ICMR_NIN_Dietary_Guidelines_Real.pdf", "publication_version": "Latest", "chunk_sequence_number": 80, "content_type": "Medical Guideline", "language": "English", "text": "/c118Eat plenty of vegetables and fruits. /c118Avoid superstitions and food taboos. /c118Do not use alcohol and tobacco. Take medicines only when prescribed. /c118Take iron, folate and calcium supplements regularly, after 14-16 weeks of pregnancy and continue the same during lactation. /c63Folic acid is essential for the synthesis of haemoglobin. /c63Folic acid deficiency leads to macrocytic anaemia. /c63Pregnant women need more of folic acid. /c63Folic acid supplements increase birth weight and reduce congenital anomalies. /c63Green leafy vegetables, legumes, nuts and liver are good sources of folic acid. /c63500 mg (0.5mg) folic acid supplementation is advised preconceptionally and through out pregnancy for women with history of congenital anomalies (neural tube defects, cleft palate).", "embedding": [0.0164412260055542, 0.011882594786584377, -0.08496560156345367, 0.03338966891169548, 0.023566938936710358, 0.06659586727619171, -0.06432333588600159, 0.1122664213180542, -0.04083585739135742, -0.05553298443555832, -0.005903216544538736, -0.04525751993060112, -0.07422351092100143, -0.05654963105916977, -0.029583824798464775, 0.0308767631649971, 0.056595392525196075, 0.05678701028227806, -0.03672002628445625, -0.03577281907200813, -0.11238721758127213, 0.016433632001280785, 0.015906084328889847, 0.06728776544332504, -0.010224904865026474, -0.07939517498016357, -0.013012262992560863, -0.03401222079992294, -0.030265050008893013, 0.020496167242527008, -0.04321327060461044, 0.019320262596011162, 0.04518438130617142, 0.007612710352987051, -0.07225742191076279, 0.06830240786075592, -0.0534093976020813, -0.04671371355652809, 0.04049960896372795, 0.005208129528909922, 0.009444892406463623, -0.012799259275197983, 